        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A–6 The answer is yes. Consider the arc of the parabola y = Ax2 inside the circle x2 + (y − 1)2 = 1, where we initially assume that A > 1/2. This intersects the circle in three points, (0, 0) and (±√2A − 1/A, (2A − 1)/A). We claim that for A sufficiently large, the length L of the parabolic arc between (O, 0) and (√2A − 1/A, (2A − 1) /A) is greater than 2, which implies the desired result by symmetry. We express L using the usual formula for arclength:",
        "bbox": [
